# Handlebars Template Rules

## Library
```typescript
import Handlebars from 'handlebars';
```

## Template Compilation
Always compile in a try/catch — invalid templates must show a human-readable error in the preview, never crash the app.

```typescript
export function compileTemplate(html: string, data: Record<string, unknown>): {
  result: string | null;
  error: string | null;
} {
  try {
    const template = Handlebars.compile(html, { strict: false });
    return { result: template(data), error: null };
  } catch (err) {
    return {
      result: null,
      error: err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Template compilation failed',
    };
  }
}
```

## Subject Line Compilation
The `subject` field also supports `{{variables}}` — always compile subject separately:

```typescript
export function compileSubject(subject: string, data: Record<string, unknown>): string {
  try {
    return Handlebars.compile(subject)(data);
  } catch {
    return subject; // fallback to raw subject on error
  }
}
```

## Mock Data Editor
- Mock data is always valid JSON — validate on every keystroke
- Show a red border + error message if JSON is invalid
- Use a debounce of 300ms before re-rendering the preview after mock data changes
- Default mock data must match all `{{variable}}` placeholders found in the template

## Preview Panel
- Render compiled HTML inside a sandboxed `<iframe>` using `srcDoc`
- Never use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` for email HTML — always use iframe
- The preview iframe should have `sandbox="allow-same-origin"` to prevent script execution
- Show a toolbar above the iframe: Desktop (600px) / Mobile (375px) width toggle

```tsx
<iframe
  srcDoc={compiledHtml}
  sandbox="allow-same-origin"
  style={{ width: previewWidth, border: 'none', height: '100%' }}
  title="Email Preview"
/>
```

## Auto-extraction of Variables
Provide a utility to scan the template HTML and extract all `{{variable}}` names so the mock data editor can auto-suggest missing keys:

```typescript
export function extractVariables(template: string): string[] {
  const regex = /\{\{[#^/]?(\w[\w.]*)\}\}/g;
  const vars = new Set<string>();
  let match;
  while ((match = regex.exec(template)) !== null) {
    vars.add(match[1]);
  }
  return Array.from(vars);
}
```
